- JIT PythonOp as a custom op (like AtenOp).

title: Transform graph to handle duplicate graph outputs
body:
In ```eval``` mode and under ```torch.no_grad()``` context, ```ORTModule``` uses the ```inference_agent``` which uses ```IOBinding``` to execute the graph. ```IOBinding``` only registers a single output for duplicate output names. As a result, when the model has duplicated outputs, the returned values from the ORT backend will only correspond to the ones registered through ```IOBinding```.

An example of duplicate outputs:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12852605/128763932-a90047ff-4ce2-4b1f-95ff-5d6616841388.png)

Example of transformed graph:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/12852605/128764004-4d62f957-e647-4cef-8185-0d10d607b97d.png)


These kind of graphs are a result of exporting a ```PyTorch``` model which returns the same value multiple times in its return statement. For example
```py
def forward(self,...):
    out = some_calculation()
    return out, out
```

This pull request addresses this problem by introducing an ```Identity``` op before graph outputs that appear multiple times through a graph transformation.

Replaces https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/8605 for context tracking.

title: Avoid round-trip copies for "pass through" subgraph inputs
body:
**Description**: 

Problem:
When an outer scope value produced on CUDA is passed to a subgraph (as an implicit or an explicit subgraph input) has no explicit consumer in the subgraph (i.e.) the only real consumer in that subgraph is another control flow node, its location value is not set in the allocation planner (defaults to CPU). When this value is in turn consumed in another nested subgraph (2 levels below the level it was produced in) on CUDA, there is a round-trip copy involved when the subgraphs are executed. When the first level subgraph executes, the control flow op thinks that the value is "required" on CPU and hence makes a CUDA -> CPU copy. When the second level subgraph executes, a copy from CPU -> CUDA is made in that scope.  

Solution:
When there is no explicit consumer of an input to a subgraph , set the location to the same location as that it was produced in in the outer scope thus deferring any copy decisions till the actual nested subgraph utilizing the value.

**Motivation and Context**
~15-17% gains for a 1P model. Should also benefit other models having a similar structure.

title: Share the execution provider instance for training
body:
Motivation: In training, there is scenarios that we will have multiple ORTModules work in the same process. each ORTModule have its own session. Currently because session own the EP instance, it will result in multiple cuda EP instance running on the same device. When use eager mode together with ORTModule also will trigger same issue, as eager mode will need access to an EP instance too. Multiple cuda EP instance on the same GPU is not efficient, further more, for some particular EP, due to hardware limitation, it currently not support multiple EP instances on same device. Ideally, we want to share the EP instance on the same device across training sessions.

This PR include following parts:
1. separate the training python module construction from the inference python module construction. Since many features (like this PR) only meaningful for training python build, have a seperate file will make things more clear, instead of have many #ifdef in the code.
2. Create a ORTTrainingEnv in orttraining python module, which maintain a global pool for available EP instances. currently only CPU and GPU execution providers support this sharing. for execution provider loaded from external, it need to provide a hash function to tell ORT how to share the instance.

title: Optimize sequence type usage on CUDA [2/n]
body:
**Description**: 

1) Register support for sequences in the CUDA kernels of `Loop` and `If`. 

2) An optimization is added for when loop carried dependencies are sequences and iteration count is > 0. In that case, we can directly move these loop carried dependencies (these are subgraph outputs) directly into the Loop's output after all the iterations - there is no need to make a copy of it. We only need to make a copy when iteration count == 0 as we can't move the Loop's inputs to the outputs.

3) We use `GPUDataTransfer` (the `IDataTransfer` abstraction) to handle cross device copies in the Loop's implementation. This is okay only as long as the copy stream being used in the data transfer class is the same as the compute stream. Otherwise, we would need explicit syncs to avoid data races. As such there is no real use-case for using a dedicated copy stream (that is different from the compute stream) as there are larger negative implications. So, as a safety check, we enforce that the copy stream is the same as the compute stream in CUDA Loop. 

No new unit tests required. Unit tests for sequences were already added when the type was supported in the CPU kernels of Loop and If.

title: [Dup] Fix SAME_UPPER/SAME_LOWER (auto_pad attribute) in ConvTranspose
body:
**Description**:
Dup of https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/5368/.

To sync the definition of SAME_UPPER/SAME_LOWER among all operators and make it same as ONNX definition, switch the logic of SAME_UPPER and SAME_LOWER in ConvTranspose.

Definition of SAME_UPPER and SAME_LOWER should be as follows:
```
if auto_pads == 'SAME_UPPER':
  pad_head = paddings / 2  # smaller one 
  pad_tail = paddings - paddings / 2  # larger one
elif auto_pads == 'SAME_LOWER':
  pad_head = paddings - paddings / 2  # larger one
  pad_tail = paddings / 2  # smaller one
```

**Motivation and Context**
The `auto_pad` attribute, `SAME_UPPER` and `SAME_LOWER` of `ConvTranspose` is different from other operators' (pool and conv related operators) `auto_pad` attribute. The behavior of same attribute should be the same among all operators. Also, it does not meet the definition in ONNX.

- `SAME_UPPER` and `SAME_LOWER` in other operators
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/c20fcf26ebc0eeda41b6fd4e54d87623030ead91/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/nn/pool_attributes.h#L149
- ConvTranspose definition in ONNX:
https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/b2ed660d0a065b8346816f2c3a95d79ca79b88c9/onnx/defs/nn/defs.cc#L1222
- A related PR in ONNX (There is a contradiction of this in ONNX):
https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/3019

title: Invertible ReluGrad
body:
ReluGrad can accept mask from either I(0) or O(0). 

def ReluGrad(dy, x_or_y) : return where((x_or_y > 0), dy, 0) 

Since x and y has the same sign, it's equivalent to pass x or y for the second input.
The amount of computation is also identical.

setting CMP0104 to OLD reverts to old behavior where CMAKE_CUDA_ARCHITECTURES is not set unless the user defines it.

title: Auto forward non method attribute lookups to the user's model and bind custom methods to ORTModule
body:
This pull request:
1. For non methods attributes: auto forwards any call made to the user's original *```torch.nn.Module```* through ```ORTModule``` by implementing the methods:
   - ```__getattr__```: Implemented for attribute lookups that could not be found in ```ORTModule``` and so a lookup is performed on the user's ```torch.nn.Module```.
   - ```__setattr__```: Implemented so that users can set attributes on their original module with ease. All attributes are set on the user provided module instead of on ```ORTModule```. This is also used as a way to signal to ```ORTModule``` that the execution graph has changed and therefore a re-export must be done before the next forward call. This is done automatically by this implementation. The auto re-export can be controlled by enabling the skip check for re-building the graph, re creating the execution agent and so on (```export ORTMODULE_SKIPCHECK_POLICY="SKIP_CHECK_BUILD_GRADIENT|SKIP_CHECK_EXECUTION_AGENT"```).
2. For methods attributes: copies user defined methods and binds them to the ```ORTModule``` instance. This is done in order to prevent the problem where user defined methods invoke the forward on the model thereby calling the `PyTorch` module implementation of forward as opposed to ```ORTModule```'s implementation of forward.

Users can now seamlessly use their training script with ```ORTModule``` without needing to change how they invoke user defined methods on their original ```torch.nn.Module```. Here is an example:
```py
# User defined torch.nn.Module 
class UserDefinedMethodsNet(torch.nn.Module): 
    def __init__(self): 
        super(UserDefinedMethodsNet, self).__init__() 

    def forward(self, ...): 
        ... 

    def custom_user_method(self, ...): 
        return some_calculation()  

    def training_step(self, ...):
        out = self(...)
        ...

# Instantiation of ORTModule 
model = UserDefinedMethodsNet() 
model = ORTModule(model) 

# Invoke user defined function 
out = model.custom_user_method() # No AttributeError since ORTModule auto forwards the call to the original module 
model.training_step(...) # ORTModule's forward will be executed and not the user defined forward
```

In addition, ```ORTModule``` checks for any attribute name collisions between the user's model and ```ORTModule```.

title: Add Gemm op to DNNL Exectution provider
body:
**Description**:
This adds the Gemm op to the DNNL Execution provider

With the addition of the Gemm op that uses the DNNL endpoint the KernelRegistry was deleted. The only Op that was in the KernelRegistry was Gemm and the implementation was not using DNNL.

With Gemm now implemented the old Gemm code was deleted. The act of deleting the KernelRegistry exposed a bug in the Training unit tests for execution providers without a KernelRegistry.  We added a fix for this that mirrors the same way it is handled in the non-training unit tests.

Now the Training ops run without needing to manually specify the DnnlExecutionProvider.  We were able to remove several instances `#ifdef USE_DNNL` from the graident_op_test.cc code. The one exception being the ConvGrad unit test.

Added two new tests one that only modifies the `alpha` attribute of Gemm another that only modified the `beta` attribute of Gemm.  This enabled figuring out which of the two attributes caused an issue.

Fix a few other bugs discovered while working on the Gemm op. 
- In some situations the DNNL subgraph code could produce a subgraph with two outputs with the same name generating an invalid graph. (Discovered when running the GlobalAveragePoolGrad unit test) **fixed**
- For dynamic shaped graphs the DNNL implementation GlobalAveragePool and GlobalMaxPool could crash. (Discovered when running the GlobalAveragePoolGrad unit test) **fixed**

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required?
This adds Gemm op to the DNNL execution provider
-  What problem does it solve?
Expands the number of operations supported by DNNL execution provider
